{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a2021b75-3c02-4db7-983d-34bca88e019f","content":"In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance **per HTTP request**. In MAUI, there's no concept of an HTTP request scope — the default scope is the **app's entire lifetime**. So `AddScoped` behaves like `AddSingleton`, and your `DbContext` is reused across all navigations, causing stale/persisted data.\n\n**Fixes:**\n\n1. **Use `AddTransient`** — gives a fresh `DbContext` each time it's injected:\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddTransient<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n2. **Create manual scopes** if you need scoped behavior tied to a page navigation:\n   ```csharp\n   using var scope = serviceScopeFactory.CreateScope();\n   var db = scope.ServiceProvider.GetRequiredService<MyDbContext>();\n   ```\n\n3. **Use `IDbContextFactory`** (recommended for MAUI/Blazor):\n   ```csharp\n   builder.Services.AddDbContextFactory<MyDbContext>(opts => ...);\n   ```\n   Then in your view model:\n   ```csharp\n   using var db = dbContextFactory.CreateDbContext();\n   ```\n\nOption 3 is the cleanest — it makes the short-lived nature of each `DbContext` explicit and avoids accidental sharing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"31671ebe-5e0b-4057-9fd5-5075f2715ed9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a common pitfall when moving from ASP.NET Core to .NET MAUI regarding dependency injection scoping. This is a conceptual question I can answer directly without needing to search any codebase.\n\nThe key issue: In ASP.NET Core, `AddScoped` creates a new instance per HTTP request. In MAUI, there are no HTTP requests, so a \"scope\" effectively lives for the entire app lifetime — making `AddScoped` behave like `AddSingleton`.","outputTokens":449,"requestId":"A441:69BE5:4D8603:5ABB65:69F007A5"},"id":"1892d21f-1111-478f-846b-d1360a75e7b7","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:04:47.219Z","parentId":"8d4042ae-ebcd-47de-b55a-4eadda74a2eb"}
